			<h1>Chinatown Chamber of Commerce</h1>
                        <audio src="/audio/en/commerce.mp3" controls>
                            Recording of Chinatown Chamber of Commerce article
                        </audio>
			<p> <br>
			    In 1983, business owners created the Chinatown Chamber of Commerce to connect residents with local businesses, national corporations, and government agencies. Over the years, the chamber has grown to include over 250 business members. The chamber now has members including small businesses in Chinatown and large organizations from across the Chicago area. 
			    <br> <br />
			    The chamber promotes and participates in community and culturally events, like the Chinese New Year Parade, the Dragon Boat Race, and the Miss Friendship Ambassador Pageant. 
			    <br> <br />
			    While there are a variety of historic businesses on Wentworth Ave, you can also find new businesses throughout Chinatown. Commercial corridors are now located on streets like Wentworth, Archer, and Cermak, and in shopping plazas like Chinatown Square. New businesses are bringing diverse cuisine, language, and culture. There are a growing number of Korean and Thai businesses, as well as Szechuan restaurants located across Chinatown.
			    <br> <br />
			    Commercial developments such as the Wintrust Arena at the McCormick Place Conference Center and “The 78,” a high-end commercial development, are bringing new development to the areas to the west of Chinatown.  South Loop development has also begun to bring new businesses and to the north of Chinatown. 
			</p>
